<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-08-07T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-08-07T10:00:00-05:00" n="812" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d812">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.5914/79</note>
                            <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-08-07T17:00:00+02:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 7, 1916, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>289. Referring to the Legation’s number 287, August 7, 3 p.m. Foreign
                                Office informs me that first publicity came to Copenhagen in a
                                despatch from Ambassador Jusserand to Bapst, French Minister here.
                                Bapst is the only one of my colleagues who openly finds our policy
                                of buying Danish West Indies objectionable. He tells Foreign Office
                                that it may lead to buying of Martinique.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Egan</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>